Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.58,0:00:04.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼: 科学家们已经花费了40年寻找\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Scientists have been hunting it for 40 years,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.92,0:00:09.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,解开宇宙奥秘的钥匙.\N{\rasEng}the key that will unlock the secrets of the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.32,0:00:12.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如今他们已经发现了.\N{\rasEng}And now they've found it.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.33,0:00:17.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子真的能告诉我们\N{\rasEng}Can the Higgs boson really tell us
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.30,0:00:19.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一切是如何诞生的？\N{\rasEng}how all creation came into being？
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.33,0:00:23.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们的存在是否应归于\N{\rasEng}Do we owe our existence to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.90,0:00:26.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一些难以捉摸而又强大的东西？\N{\rasEng}something so elusive yet so powerful？
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.44,0:00:30.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是否存在上帝粒子？\N{\rasEng}Is there a God particle？
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.18,0:00:40.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,空间、时间、生命本身,\N{\rasEng}Space,time,life itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.22,0:00:48.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙的奥秘尽在穿越虫洞.\N{\rasEng}The secrets of the cosmos lie through the wormhole.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.16,0:00:52.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,== 翻译： {\c&H00FF00&}Allegro1756{\c} == \N== 时间轴、校对： {\c&H00FF00&}elderman{\c} ==
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.19,0:00:58.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是否存在上帝粒子？ \N{\rasEng}Is There a God Particle？
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.04,0:01:05.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们如何存在于宇宙之中呢？\N{\rasEng}How did we get to be here in this universe？
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.88,0:01:10.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家们称宇宙诞生于一场纯粹能量的爆炸,\N{\rasEng}Scientists say our universe began as a burst of pure energy,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.85,0:01:15.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,以某种方式,能量转变为物质,\N{\rasEng}but somehow,that energy transformed itself into matter
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.45,0:01:18.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最终形成了恒星、行星,\N{\rasEng}which eventually became stars,planets,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.66,0:01:21.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,以及所有组成你和我的元素.\N{\rasEng}and the stuff that makes up you and me.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.49,0:01:23.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们的宇宙\N{\rasEng}Instead of being
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.26,0:01:26.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,没有变成瞬时的飞掠过的火球,\N{\rasEng}a fleeting fireball gone in an instant,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.10,0:01:30.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而是胶着了数万亿年.\N{\rasEng}our universe has stuck around for billions of years.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.00,0:01:34.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学家们很久之前就怀疑\N{\rasEng}Physicists have long suspected there must be
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.31,0:01:37.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一定存在某些看不见的力场散布于整个宇宙,\N{\rasEng}some invisible force field spread across the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.91,0:01:42.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这种神秘的力量将能量变为实体物质.\N{\rasEng}mysteriously turning energy into solid matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.91,0:01:45.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,现在,科学家们最终证明了\N{\rasEng}Now scientists have at last proven
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.98,0:01:49.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,理论中的这种力场是真实存在的.\N{\rasEng}that this theoretical force field is real.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.72,0:01:51.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们从这个力场中获得了\N{\rasEng}They have produced from it
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.46,0:01:55.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个亚原子粒子--希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}a subatomic particle known as the Higgs boson,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.63,0:01:58.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就是所谓的上帝粒子.\N{\rasEng}the so-called God particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.56,0:02:01.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,上帝粒子能够解释我们存在的原因么？\N{\rasEng}Can it explain the mystery of our creation？
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.64,0:02:09.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你见过玩陀螺吗？\N{\rasEng}Have you ever watched a spinning top？
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.51,0:02:12.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,还是孩子的时候,我记得自己\N{\rasEng}As a kid,I remember being mesmerized
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.91,0:02:17.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,喜欢看画着多种图案的陀螺旋转,\N{\rasEng}watching the painted shapes spinning on mine.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.65,0:02:20.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那些图案变得朦胧模糊,\N{\rasEng}The pattern became a ghostly blur.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.12,0:02:24.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,似乎我可以把手指穿过这些图案,\N{\rasEng}Looked like I could stick my finger right through it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.69,0:02:29.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可一旦转动停止,图案又变成原来那样清晰.\N{\rasEng}But once it stopped moving,the pattern became solid again.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.56,0:02:34.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物质的纯粹属性长久以来困惑着物理学家.\N{\rasEng}The solid nature of matter has long puzzled physicists.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.43,0:02:35.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,过去四十年里,\N{\rasEng}Over the last four decades,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.83,0:02:37.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们一直在考虑物质的存在是否\N{\rasEng}they have wondered if matter is solid
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.87,0:02:39.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是由于被称作上帝粒子的\N{\rasEng}because of the Higgs boson,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.84,0:02:43.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子造成的.\N{\rasEng}the so-called God particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.44,0:02:45.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你知道人们到底想把它称作什么,\N{\rasEng}You know what they really wanted to call it,right？
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.08,0:02:46.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,人们想称之为上帝[哔--]粒子....\N{\rasEng}They wanted to call it the God [bleep] particle...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.71,0:02:48.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这可能不能在电视台上播.\N{\rasEng}You probably can't put that on TV though.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.58,0:02:50.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...为了寻找它,我们花费了大量的\N{\rasEng}...given the amount of time and money we've spent
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.15,0:02:50.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,时间和金钱,\N{\rasEng}looking for this thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.95,0:02:52.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可我们都没能发现.\N{\rasEng}And we've missed it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.05,0:02:53.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,“哦[哔--]该死,这个粒子到底在哪儿？”\N{\rasEng}"Oh [bleep] damn. Where is that particle？"
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.62,0:02:57.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Dan Hooper和Patrick Fox是理论物理学家,\N{\rasEng}Dan Hooper and Patrick Fox are theoretical physicists
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.99,0:03:00.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就职于费米国家加速器实验室,\N{\rasEng}at the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.53,0:03:02.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就在芝加哥城外.\N{\rasEng}just outside of Chicago.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.96,0:03:06.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,和上千名物理学家一样,他们在职业生涯中\N{\rasEng}Like thousands of physicists,they have spent their careers
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.90,0:03:09.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,等待着希格斯玻色子会在\N{\rasEng}waiting for the Higgs boson to reveal itself
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.97,0:03:13.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,高速粒子对撞实验中现形.\N{\rasEng}in high-speed particle-collision experiments.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.87,0:03:15.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们已经寻找了很久了,\N{\rasEng}It's something we've been looking for for a long time.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.67,0:03:17.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果没有上帝粒子,\N{\rasEng}The universe would be very different
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.64,0:03:19.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙会变得与预想大不相同.\N{\rasEng}if it weren't for the God particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.68,0:03:24.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,实际上,物理学家们认为有那么短暂的一瞬间,\N{\rasEng}Physicists believe,in fact,that there was a brief moment
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.92,0:03:28.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙中并不存在上帝粒子.\N{\rasEng}when the universe lived without the God particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.89,0:03:31.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在时间出现的时候,\N{\rasEng}It was at the beginning of time itself,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.36,0:03:35.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这比出现物理学家和这个游乐场还要早.\N{\rasEng}long before there were physicists and arcades.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.63,0:03:40.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,把这个漂浮曲棍球桌想象成宇宙,\N{\rasEng}Imagine this air hockey table is the entire universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.03,0:03:43.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在它诞生时的大爆炸中,\N{\rasEng}When it was born in the big bang,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.54,0:03:45.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学家们认为这个时候\N{\rasEng}physicists think there were only
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.80,0:03:49.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,只有纯能量无质量的粒子.\N{\rasEng}massless particles of pure energy.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.71,0:03:50.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么这时你能看到的是\N{\rasEng}So,what you can see here is that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.94,0:03:52.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,所有的粒子以相同的速度运动,\N{\rasEng}all the particles are moving around at the same speed,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.81,0:03:54.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,用这个速度就是光速.\N{\rasEng}at the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.05,0:03:57.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们在整个宇宙中基本没有质量.\N{\rasEng}They're all essentially massless in the whole universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.18,0:04:00.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是宇宙并没有以这种状态持续很久,\N{\rasEng}But the universe did not remain that way for very long.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.69,0:04:03.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就在几分之一秒后,\N{\rasEng}After only a fraction of a second,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.69,0:04:05.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,有些东西变了.\N{\rasEng}something changed.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.92,0:04:09.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像有人扳了控制杆,\N{\rasEng}Almost like someone pulled a lever
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.26,0:04:13.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,使许多粒子慢慢停下来.\N{\rasEng}that made many of the particles grind to a halt.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.57,0:04:15.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,某一点时,希格斯场打开了,\N{\rasEng}At some point,the Higgs field turned on,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.90,0:04:18.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就使得一些粒子获得了质量,\N{\rasEng}and that made some of the particles acquire a mass,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.10,0:04:20.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,同时意味着它们不再以光速运动.\N{\rasEng}which meant they stopped traveling at the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.24,0:04:21.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,光子,以黄色表示的,\N{\rasEng}The photons,the yellow ones,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.57,0:04:23.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,继续以光速运动,\N{\rasEng}are zipping around at the speed of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.31,0:04:25.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而红色和绿色的表示得到了质量,\N{\rasEng}whereas the red and the green have acquired a mass
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.51,0:04:26.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,由于希格斯机制而导致\N{\rasEng}thanks to the Higgs mechanism
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.85,0:04:28.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,运动速度变缓.\N{\rasEng}and travel more slowly.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.78,0:04:32.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学家们认为刚刚在大爆炸之后,\N{\rasEng}Physicists believe that right after the Big Bang,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.95,0:04:37.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙在冷却的过程中,希格斯场开始发挥作用了.\N{\rasEng}the universe began to cool,and the Higgs field turned on.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.72,0:04:40.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一些粒子开始和希格斯场相互作用\N{\rasEng}Some particles began to interact with the field
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.66,0:04:42.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来获得质量.\N{\rasEng}and acquired mass.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.79,0:04:46.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另一些粒子则保持了无质量的纯能量状态.\N{\rasEng}Other particles remained massless bundles of energy.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.90,0:04:49.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,几十年里,\N{\rasEng}In the decades for which
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.03,0:04:51.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家们一直在撞碎粒子\N{\rasEng}scientists have been smashing together particles
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.34,0:04:54.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来探究亚原子世界,\N{\rasEng}to probe the subatomic world,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.14,0:04:57.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们已经发现了两种基本类型的粒子.\N{\rasEng}they have found two basic types of particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.94,0:05:00.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一种是费米子,\N{\rasEng}There are fermions,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.38,0:05:03.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一组携带有质量的粒子,\N{\rasEng}a group of massive particles that carry matter,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.95,0:05:06.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,和玻色子,\N{\rasEng}and there are bosons,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.75,0:05:10.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,携带能量的无质量粒子.\N{\rasEng}massless particles that carry force.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.29,0:05:12.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,没有希格斯场的存在,\N{\rasEng}Without the existence of the Higgs,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.49,0:05:16.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,所有的粒子都会是无质量的.\N{\rasEng}all particles would be massless.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.33,0:05:17.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么如果没有希格斯场,\N{\rasEng}So,if there was no Higgs field,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.90,0:05:20.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你会有一些其他的力的载体.\N{\rasEng}you would have had these other force carriers.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.33,0:05:21.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们也是无质量的,\N{\rasEng}They would have been massless,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.80,0:05:23.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,因此,就像光子,\N{\rasEng}and therefore,like the particles of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.77,0:05:25.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们都会以光速运动,\N{\rasEng}they would move at the speed of light.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.07,0:05:27.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,没有这些质量,就绝对不可能出现\N{\rasEng}And without these masses,you can never have
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.24,0:05:29.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,各种原子或化学等之类的我们在宇宙中发现的\N{\rasEng}atoms or chemistry or any of the interesting stuff
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.81,0:05:31.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,有趣的东西,\N{\rasEng}we find in our universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.18,0:05:32.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,组成你和我的物质也不会\N{\rasEng}The things that you and I are made up of
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.58,0:05:33.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,结合到一起\N{\rasEng}wouldn't be able to clump and coalesce
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.95,0:05:34.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并减速.\N{\rasEng}and slow down.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.85,0:05:36.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,没有任何结构,也就没有生命. 是的.\N{\rasEng}No structure,no life. Right.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.21,0:05:37.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一切都会很无聊. 对.\N{\rasEng}Boredom. Yep.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.25,0:05:40.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,多亏了希格斯场,\N{\rasEng}Thanks to the Higgs,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.85,0:05:42.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们的宇宙才能以现在的形式存在足够久,\N{\rasEng}our universe hung around long enough
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.92,0:05:46.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,以形成像人类这样的具有复杂结构的生命形式.\N{\rasEng}for complex structures likes human life to form.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.66,0:05:51.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是为什么创造物质的希格斯场会启动呢？\N{\rasEng}But why did the matter-creating Higgs field turn on？
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.50,0:05:55.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,包括Dan和Patrick在内的许多科学家\N{\rasEng}Many scientists,including Dan and Patrick,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.10,0:05:57.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,认为是大爆炸纯粹的暴力\N{\rasEng}think the sheer violence of the Big Bang
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.77,0:06:01.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,造成了希格斯场的运作.\N{\rasEng}jostled the field into action.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.11,0:06:02.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么到现在,我一直在\N{\rasEng}So,up until now,I've been
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.41,0:06:04.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,用我的手控制希格斯机制的开或关.\N{\rasEng}turning the Higgs mechanism on and off by hand.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.68,0:06:06.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是当然,在早期的宇宙,\N{\rasEng}But of course,in the early universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.41,0:06:07.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不是以这种方式进行的.\N{\rasEng}it didn't happen that way.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.75,0:06:10.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像水在你冷冻它的时候\N{\rasEng}And just like water freezes all on its own
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.42,0:06:12.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,自己就会结冰,\N{\rasEng}when you cool it,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.12,0:06:15.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯机制也会在宇宙冷却时\N{\rasEng}the Higgs mechanism will turn on all by itself
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.29,0:06:16.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,自动启动.\N{\rasEng}as the universe cools.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.49,0:06:18.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这根台球杆假设代表了\N{\rasEng}So,this pool cue is supposed to represent
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.09,0:06:20.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯机制自身的不稳定.\N{\rasEng}how unstable the Higgs mechanism was all by itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.93,0:06:21.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像你看到的这样...\N{\rasEng}And as you can see...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.86,0:06:23.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就这样. ...倒下去了.\N{\rasEng}Voilà. ...It just falls over.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.56,0:06:26.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家认为希格斯场,\N{\rasEng}Scientists think the Higgs field,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.86,0:06:29.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,即是使能量转变成\N{\rasEng}the force that turned a ball of energy
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.03,0:06:30.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们物质宇宙的力,\N{\rasEng}into our physical universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.50,0:06:32.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,完全是自动启动的.\N{\rasEng}turned on all by itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.67,0:06:35.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但也有一些人说这并不是偶然的,\N{\rasEng}But some will say that it was no accident,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.64,0:06:39.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,必定有某位造物主将其启动.\N{\rasEng}and it must have been turned on by a creator.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.51,0:06:42.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而若要知道一切创始之谜\N{\rasEng}That mystery of creation may be answered
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.08,0:06:45.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就需要更进一步的了解希格斯场.\N{\rasEng}if we learn more about the Higgs field.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.55,0:06:49.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家致力于扰动希格斯场\N{\rasEng}Scientists have been trying to disturb the field enough
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.29,0:06:54.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来产生一个希格斯玻色子以便研究.\N{\rasEng}to make it produce a Higgs boson so they can study it.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.03,0:06:56.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样物理学家制造了\N{\rasEng}It's an effort that has made physicists construct
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.33,0:06:59.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学史上最大的仪器,\N{\rasEng}the most powerful machine in the history of science,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.40,0:07:04.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,大型强子对撞机,简称LHC.\N{\rasEng}the Large Hadron Collider,or the LHC.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.10,0:07:09.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,过去四十年中,Lyn Evans负责建造\N{\rasEng}Lyn Evans has been responsible for building
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.41,0:07:12.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,位于瑞士日内瓦的CERN(欧洲核子研究组织)中的\N{\rasEng}every particle accelerator at CERN in Geneva
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.78,0:07:15.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,每台粒子加速器.\N{\rasEng}for the past four decades.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.51,0:07:19.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他创造的每台机器至今仍在工作.\N{\rasEng}All the machines he created are still working.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.22,0:07:23.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,事实上,它们分阶段的共同工作.\N{\rasEng}In fact,they all work together in stages.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.39,0:07:26.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,每一个老旧的机器现在负责\N{\rasEng}Each older one is now responsible for
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.46,0:07:29.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,给予粒子一个增加的推力,\N{\rasEng}giving the particles an incremental push,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.56,0:07:32.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,赋予其越来越多的能量,\N{\rasEng}packing them with more and more energy,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.30,0:07:34.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最终将其注入巨大的、\N{\rasEng}and eventually feeding them into the giant,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.73,0:07:40.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,17英里(27.36公里)长的环形LHC中.\N{\rasEng}17-mile-long ring that is the LHC.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.07,0:07:43.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Evans: 我1969年的时候来到CERN,\N{\rasEng}Evans: I came to CERN in 1969.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.34,0:07:45.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我的第一个工作就是研究\N{\rasEng}My first job was working on what is called
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.94,0:07:48.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,双等离子体离子源,\N{\rasEng}the dual plasmatron ion source,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:48.38,0:07:50.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,也就是质子的来源.\N{\rasEng}which is actually the source of the protons.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.55,0:07:52.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后就把它们加速.\N{\rasEng}And then,they are accelerated.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.72,0:07:54.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,从线性加速器,\N{\rasEng}From the linear accelerator,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.12,0:07:56.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,到助推器中获得更高的能量,\N{\rasEng}they go into a booster to get higher energy
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.29,0:07:58.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,接着进入超质子同步加速器,\N{\rasEng}and then into the super proton synchrotron,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.19,0:08:00.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就是我70年代开始工作的地方,\N{\rasEng}which I worked on in the '70s,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.49,0:08:04.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最后进入大型强子对撞机.\N{\rasEng}and finally into the Large Hadron Collider.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.20,0:08:06.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：正是由于过去几十年中\N{\rasEng}Freeman: As particle accelerators
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.06,0:08:09.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,先进的粒子加速器,\N{\rasEng}have advanced over the past few decades,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.03,0:08:11.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们能够让粒子\N{\rasEng}they have been able to get particles
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.17,0:08:13.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,获得越来越多的能量,\N{\rasEng}to higher and higher energies,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.94,0:08:15.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就可以让他们\N{\rasEng}allowing them to create
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.31,0:08:17.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在每次碰撞中创造\N{\rasEng}more and more massive new particles
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.88,0:08:19.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,更多种类的新粒子.\N{\rasEng}with each collision.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.95,0:08:24.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,更为老旧的加速器只有足够的能量\N{\rasEng}The older accelerators only had enough energy
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.68,0:08:27.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来使两个质子撞击形成一个新粒子...\N{\rasEng}to smash together two protons and make a new particle...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.99,0:08:28.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Aah! Aah!\N{\rasEng}Aah! Aah!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.95,0:08:31.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...而这个粒子仅是质量加倍而已.\N{\rasEng}...with just double the mass.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.29,0:08:34.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是理论家预测希格斯粒子的重量\N{\rasEng}But theorists predict the Higgs weighs
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.06,0:08:37.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,至少是一个质子的100倍.\N{\rasEng}at least 100 times as much as a proton.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.33,0:08:39.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学法则认定\N{\rasEng}The laws of physics say that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.30,0:08:42.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果你给质子额外的动能,\N{\rasEng}if you give protons extra kinetic energy,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.77,0:08:46.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你能使它们撞击形成一个新粒子,\N{\rasEng}you can smash them together to form a new particle
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.07,0:08:52.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,其重量要比它们所有部分的总和高出许多倍.\N{\rasEng}that weighs many times more than the sum of their parts.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.04,0:08:53.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Evans：这就又回到了\N{\rasEng}Evans: Well,it all goes back to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.61,0:08:55.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最著名的科学方程式,\N{\rasEng}the most famous equation in science,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.41,0:08:57.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,e=mc平方.\N{\rasEng}e=mc squared.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.25,0:08:59.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在LHC中,我们把能量转变成质量,\N{\rasEng}In the LHC,we are converting energy into mass,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.82,0:09:01.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果你想制作出更重的东西,\N{\rasEng}and if you want to make very heavy objects,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.89,0:09:03.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你就需要非常多的能量.\N{\rasEng}you need a high energy.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.19,0:09:09.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：把粒子物理学家想象成高尔夫运动员,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Think of particle physicists as golfers
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.13,0:09:12.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,只是把击打的质子变成高尔夫球.\N{\rasEng}hitting protons instead of golf balls.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.26,0:09:15.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,多年之后,他们就会变成越来越好的俱乐部(球队).\N{\rasEng}Over the years,they have gotten better and better clubs.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.10,0:09:20.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Evans：打个比方,我认为这根高尔夫球杆,\N{\rasEng}Evans: To make an analogy,I think this pitching wedge,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.00,0:09:23.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你可以想象是那些60年代的加速器,\N{\rasEng}you can think of as the machines of the '60s.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.34,0:09:27.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我能用它将球击出大概120码远,\N{\rasEng}This will take me about roughly 120 yards,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.04,0:09:28.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像这样,\N{\rasEng}something like that,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.88,0:09:32.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,因为它不能提供足够的击打能量...\N{\rasEng}because it doesn't have enough energy...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.88,0:09:35.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,将球打出很远.\N{\rasEng}to go very far.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.25,0:09:39.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,接下来这根就是质子-反质子对撞机,\N{\rasEng}Then,the next one was the proton-antiproton collider.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.16,0:09:42.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,质子-反质子对撞机非常强大,\N{\rasEng}The proton-antiproton collider was much more powerful,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.36,0:09:45.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,对,有点像七号铁杆.\N{\rasEng}and,yeah,a bit like a seven iron.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.33,0:09:48.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这次,粒子就可以获得更多的能量...\N{\rasEng}This time,the particles will get more energy...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.30,0:09:56.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...飞出更远的距离.\N{\rasEng}...and will go quite a bit further.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.07,0:09:58.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最后,当然,现在我们得到的--\N{\rasEng}And finally,of course,now we've got --
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.61,0:10:00.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最后我们使用的是这台仪器,\N{\rasEng}at last,we've got the machine
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.65,0:10:03.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可以产生出希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}that can produce the Higgs boson.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.98,0:10:07.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果你想打个比方,\N{\rasEng}And if you want an analogy with that,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.72,0:10:09.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这是我忠实可靠的球棒,\N{\rasEng}this is my faithful driver.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.16,0:10:13.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来吧.\N{\rasEng}So,here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.60,0:10:23.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,的确打得很远.\N{\rasEng}And that really moves it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.87,0:10:27.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：制造出像希格斯玻色子一样重的粒子\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Making a particle as heavy as the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.54,0:10:29.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,需要比之前加速器产生的\N{\rasEng}requires far more energy
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.21,0:10:32.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,更多的能量.\N{\rasEng}than any previous accelerator has ever produced.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.58,0:10:36.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Lyn和CERN的庞大工程师团队\N{\rasEng}Lyn and the enormous team of engineers at CERN
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.28,0:10:40.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,已经把这项技术推进到极限.\N{\rasEng}have had to push their technology to the limits.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.49,0:10:41.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Evans：每次加速粒子,\N{\rasEng}Evans: Every time the particles come around,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.95,0:10:43.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们获得一点点推动,\N{\rasEng}they get a little kick,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.69,0:10:45.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,逐步提升他们的能量\N{\rasEng}increasing their energy incrementally
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.96,0:10:48.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,直到能量充满.\N{\rasEng}until we get up to the full energy reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.59,0:10:52.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：物理学家最终得到了他们想要的能量.\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Physicists finally have the power they need.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.70,0:10:55.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是捕获和研究希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}But capturing and studying the Higgs boson
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.50,0:10:58.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,需要的不仅仅是粗暴的力量.\N{\rasEng}is about more than brute force.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.24,0:11:01.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就像在干草堆中寻针--\N{\rasEng}It's a quest to pull a needle from a haystack --
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.74,0:11:07.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个由亿万个亚原子粒子构成的干草堆.\N{\rasEng}a haystack made of trillions of subatomic particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.44,0:11:12.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,对于大多数宗教信仰者来说,\N{\rasEng}For most religious believers,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.78,0:11:16.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,神不能够被看到或者听到,\N{\rasEng}God cannot be seen or heard.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.32,0:11:20.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是他或她存在的迹象就在我们周围.\N{\rasEng}But signs of his or her presence are felt all around us.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.99,0:11:24.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子很难发现,\N{\rasEng}The Higgs boson is almost as elusive,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.49,0:11:28.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这也就是为什么追踪它变得很有挑战性.\N{\rasEng}which is why the chase for it has been so challenging.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.70,0:11:31.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子可以在十亿分之一\N{\rasEng}The Higgs can pop in and out of existence
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.47,0:11:35.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,或一万亿分之一秒内出现并消失,\N{\rasEng}in one billionth of a trillionth of a second
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.74,0:11:38.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,只留下细微的证据\N{\rasEng}and only leaves behind the faintest of evidence
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.27,0:11:40.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,证明它存在过.\N{\rasEng}that it was ever there.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.64,0:11:44.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么科学家如何去寻找\N{\rasEng}So,how do scientists find something
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.48,0:11:47.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,永远不可见的东西呢？\N{\rasEng}that can never be seen？
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.85,0:11:53.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当物理学家Joe Incandela还是个孩子的时候,\N{\rasEng}When physicist Joe Incandela was a kid,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.82,0:11:57.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他的父母希望他能成为一名玻璃雕塑家.\N{\rasEng}his mom and dad hoped he would become a glass sculptor.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.99,0:12:00.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela: 我小时候对艺术非常感兴趣,\N{\rasEng}Incandela: I was very much interested in art as a kid.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.23,0:12:02.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我父母也强烈鼓励我.\N{\rasEng}My parents encouraged that very strongly.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.86,0:12:04.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们也曾对艺术很感兴趣.\N{\rasEng}They'd been very interested in art.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.50,0:12:07.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我发现我最喜欢的一位吹玻璃者\N{\rasEng}And I discovered one of my favorite glassblowers
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.80,0:12:09.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是名化学家,\N{\rasEng}was a chemist,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.17,0:12:10.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这算是我去大学学习化学\N{\rasEng}and so,that kind of gave me an excuse
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.74,0:12:12.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,的一个理由吧.\N{\rasEng}to go to college and study chemistry.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.94,0:12:15.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后我学习化学的时候,还需要学习物理,\N{\rasEng}And so,when I took chemistry,I had to take physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.51,0:12:17.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这又恰好符合我的兴趣,\N{\rasEng}And that just immediately hit me.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.85,0:12:19.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这真的很神奇,\N{\rasEng}This was really fascinating.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.15,0:12:20.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这才是我想要学习的东西.\N{\rasEng}This was the stuff I wanted to study.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.82,0:12:24.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Joe现在是LHC的\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Joe is now the leader of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.32,0:12:28.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,两个主要项目的其中之一的领导者,\N{\rasEng}one of the two major experiments at the LHC.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.16,0:12:32.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他引导着世界上千名物理学家,\N{\rasEng}He directs thousands of physicists from around the world
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.39,0:12:35.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们都有着同样的疑问,\N{\rasEng}who are all on the same quest
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.23,0:12:38.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希望能够发现我们知道的一切\N{\rasEng}to figure out how and why
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.60,0:12:42.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是如何和为什么会存在.\N{\rasEng}we and everything we know exist.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.54,0:12:44.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela: 我们真的努力去理解\N{\rasEng}Incandela: We're really trying to understand
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.14,0:12:46.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们在宇宙中的位置.\N{\rasEng}our place in the universe,you know？
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.44,0:12:47.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一切都是由什么构成,\N{\rasEng}What is everything made of,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.94,0:12:49.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而它们又如何成为这样,\N{\rasEng}and how did it become what it is？
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.24,0:12:50.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这类基本问题.\N{\rasEng}These sort of fundamental questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.88,0:12:57.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Joe认为LHC可以解答这些问题.\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Joe believes the LHC will answer these questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.42,0:13:02.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在LHC中的碰撞重建了刚刚大爆炸之后\N{\rasEng}The collisions at the LHC recreate the energy conditions
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.02,0:13:05.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,发生的能量状况.\N{\rasEng}that happened just after the Big Bang.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.59,0:13:08.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家试图对希格斯场启动\N{\rasEng}Scientists are trying to gain some insight
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.76,0:13:11.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并扩散到整个宇宙的时候\N{\rasEng}into the moment when the Higgs field turned on
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.97,0:13:14.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,获得更多的了解,\N{\rasEng}and spread across the entire universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.70,0:13:18.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯场创造了物质、恒星、\N{\rasEng}creating matter,the stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.01,0:13:20.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最后创造了我们.\N{\rasEng}and eventually us.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.64,0:13:24.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯场的力的载体是希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}The force of the Higgs field is carried by the Higgs boson,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.35,0:13:27.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而玻色子的产生只能通过\N{\rasEng}and a boson can only be detected by creating
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.88,0:13:31.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,创造场中的一个能量扰动.\N{\rasEng}an energy disturbance in the field.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.55,0:13:33.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela:制造出希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}Incandela: Turns out the Higgs is actually
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.49,0:13:36.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就在某种程度上决定了整个宇宙\N{\rasEng}determining the whole universe in some way,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.66,0:13:38.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,所处的状态,\N{\rasEng}what state it's in,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.19,0:13:40.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,还有这些粒子存在的表现形式.\N{\rasEng}and how these particles will manifest themselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.73,0:13:44.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么如果我们使用像LHC这样的加速器,\N{\rasEng}So,if we take an accelerator like the LHC,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.30,0:13:46.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并提供足够的能量,\N{\rasEng}and we provide enough energy,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.47,0:13:48.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后将质子撞在一起,\N{\rasEng}and we smash the protons together,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.37,0:13:50.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你就能够从杂乱的背景中\N{\rasEng}we can actually pull,if you like,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.47,0:13:52.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,找出希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}a Higgs particle out of this fabric
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.57,0:13:54.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并对其进行研究.\N{\rasEng}and study it.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.54,0:13:57.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：正如这些\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Just like these glass balls
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.04,0:13:59.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,充满很多东西的玻璃球,\N{\rasEng}are filled with a bunch of stuff,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.21,0:14:03.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在LHC中碰撞的质子中\N{\rasEng}the protons that are smashed together at the LHC
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.38,0:14:05.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,也充斥着很多东西--\N{\rasEng}are also filled with stuff --
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.79,0:14:09.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如夸克和胶子.\N{\rasEng}particles called quarks and gluons.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.49,0:14:12.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当质子碰撞时,\N{\rasEng}When protons collide,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.13,0:14:15.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,上千个新粒子从中迸出.\N{\rasEng}thousands of new particles come shooting out.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.43,0:14:19.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,研究碰撞余波是个辛苦的工作,\N{\rasEng}Studying the aftermath is a painstaking job,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.53,0:14:23.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像从一大堆碎玻璃中筛出我们需要的.\N{\rasEng}like sifting through piles of shattered glass.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.10,0:14:25.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela: 我们在找的是特定的模式,\N{\rasEng}Incandela: We're looking for certain patterns.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.27,0:14:27.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,能量、粒子和碎片残骸以多种方式\N{\rasEng}The energy,the particles,the debris
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.61,0:14:30.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,散布到检测器周围,\N{\rasEng}is scattered around the detector in various ways,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.28,0:14:33.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,对于一个希格斯玻色子,你就需要非常特定的模式,\N{\rasEng}and for a Higgs,you have very specific patterns
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.05,0:14:35.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就依赖于它的衰退.\N{\rasEng}depending on the decay that's involved.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.58,0:14:40.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：但是上帝粒子赐予物理学家的是曲折,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: But the God particle has blessed physicists with a twist.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.49,0:14:44.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在能够辨认出它之前就已经消失了.\N{\rasEng}It always vanishes before it can be spotted.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.93,0:14:46.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子的衰退几乎是即时的,\N{\rasEng}The Higgs decays almost instantly.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.86,0:14:49.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它的寿命极短,我们无法检测.\N{\rasEng}Its lifetime is so short,we can't measure it.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.80,0:14:55.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样我们就检测了它的衰退产物.\N{\rasEng}And so,we detect it by its decay products.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.67,0:14:58.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：为了检测希格斯玻色子,像Joe这样的物理学家\N{\rasEng}Freeman: To detect a Higgs,physicists like Joe
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.57,0:15:01.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,需要检查质子碰撞后的余波\N{\rasEng}have to look at the aftermath of proton collisions
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.88,0:15:05.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来找出它存在的证据.\N{\rasEng}to figure out what the original particles were.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.35,0:15:06.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果Joe能够分析\N{\rasEng}If Joe could analyze
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.81,0:15:09.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这场玻璃球碰撞后的每一片残骸,\N{\rasEng}each piece of debris in this glass collision
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.88,0:15:12.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并计算出它们的抛射轨道,\N{\rasEng}and calculate its trajectory,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.85,0:15:14.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他就能基于\N{\rasEng}he could reconstruct the crash
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.72,0:15:17.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些残留的部分重建碰撞.\N{\rasEng}based on the remnants that came out of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.43,0:15:19.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela: 我们看到的大多数的相互作用,\N{\rasEng}Incandela: Most of the interactions that we see,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.76,0:15:21.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都是直接产生了我们能够识别\N{\rasEng}they immediately create a pattern
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.36,0:15:23.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但又不感兴趣的模式,\N{\rasEng}that we recognize as not interesting,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.13,0:15:24.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们就能将它们排除.\N{\rasEng}and we can reject them.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.57,0:15:26.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,迄今,我们已经排除了\N{\rasEng}So,we reject,by far,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.30,0:15:28.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,碰撞的大部分痕迹.\N{\rasEng}the vast majority of the collisions.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.30,0:15:31.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：值得研究的产物唯有那些\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The only collisions worth studying are when
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.87,0:15:35.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,质子完美对齐下的撞击.\N{\rasEng}the components of the protons are perfectly aligned.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.64,0:15:39.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果一个质子中的一个夸克同另一个质子中的\N{\rasEng}If a quark inside one proton makes a head-on impact
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.11,0:15:41.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个夸克迎头撞击,\N{\rasEng}with a quark inside the other,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.12,0:15:43.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样几乎所有的碰撞能量\N{\rasEng}then almost all the energy of the collision
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.88,0:15:47.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,集中于一个地方.\N{\rasEng}is concentrated in one place.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.49,0:15:51.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样就足够产生一个希格斯场的波动,\N{\rasEng}This creates a strong enough ripple in the Higgs field
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.16,0:15:54.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来产生一个希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}to make a Higgs boson.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.16,0:15:58.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但这样的撞击几乎从没发生过.\N{\rasEng}But this type of collision almost never happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.73,0:16:01.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,现在这些罕见事件,好吧--真的很罕见.\N{\rasEng}Now,those are rare events,okay -- really rare.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.27,0:16:04.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么大体来说,\N{\rasEng}So,roughly speaking,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.17,0:16:07.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,产生一个希格斯玻色子的概率是一万亿分之一.\N{\rasEng}a Higgs production is almost one in a trillion.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.51,0:16:11.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：自从LHC启动以来,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Since the LHC has been running,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.78,0:16:16.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,已经进行了大约1000万亿次撞击.\N{\rasEng}it has produced about 1,000 trillion collisions.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.68,0:16:18.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela: 如果你有1000万亿个沙粒,\N{\rasEng}Incandela: If you had 1,000 trillion grains of sand,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.95,0:16:21.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你就能用它们填满一个奥林匹克规模的游泳池.\N{\rasEng}you would fill an olympic-sized swimming pool.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.09,0:16:22.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[ Zip! Crunch! ]\N{\rasEng}[ Zip! Crunch! ]
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.49,0:16:24.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼: 但是只有几百个撞击\N{\rasEng}Freeman: But only a few hundred of those collisions
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.33,0:16:25.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可能会产生希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}might produce a Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.86,0:16:26.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ugh.\N{\rasEng}Ugh.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.83,0:16:28.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,几百粒沙子\N{\rasEng}A few hundred grains of sand
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.90,0:16:32.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,仅能盖住你的指尖.\N{\rasEng}would just cover the tip of your finger.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.17,0:16:37.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这看起来像是不可能的任务,\N{\rasEng}It is a seemingly impossible task,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.10,0:16:39.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是震惊世界的是,\N{\rasEng}but to the world's astonishment,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.14,0:16:41.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Joe和上千名物理学家\N{\rasEng}Joe and thousands of other physicists
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.74,0:16:44.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,推翻了这种不可能.\N{\rasEng}pulled off the unfathomable.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.18,0:16:45.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,涉及其中的仅是非常少的痕迹,\N{\rasEng}There's very few events involved,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.81,0:16:47.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们能够追踪它从哪里来.\N{\rasEng}and we can trace where this comes from.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.82,0:16:51.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：2012年七月四日,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: On July 4,2012,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.09,0:16:53.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Joe有幸能宣布\N{\rasEng}Joe had the honor of announcing
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.19,0:16:58.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在LHC工作的团队向前迈了一大步.\N{\rasEng}that the teams at the LHC had made a giant step forward.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.76,0:17:01.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们检测到了一个新粒子,\N{\rasEng}They had detected a new particle
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.33,0:17:06.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,重量在125到126兆电子伏,\N{\rasEng}that weighed between 125 and 126 giga-electron volts,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.50,0:17:10.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,符合对希格斯玻色子重量的预测.\N{\rasEng}the predicted range of the mass of the Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.40,0:17:12.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...因为这些结果现在由全球\N{\rasEng}...because these results are now global
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.27,0:17:14.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,和全人类所共享,\N{\rasEng}and shared by all of mankind.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.34,0:17:16.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,所以,非常感谢你们所有人.\N{\rasEng}So,I thank you for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.24,0:17:17.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[鼓掌]\N{\rasEng}[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.41,0:17:20.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我的职业生涯中从没见过这样的情况,\N{\rasEng}I've never seen anything like it in my career.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.61,0:17:25.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,大家非常兴奋,人们都很高兴.\N{\rasEng}There was a lot of excitement. People were very happy.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.29,0:17:27.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Fox：很难相信,这像是人们去看\N{\rasEng}Fox: It was just incredible,like going to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.56,0:17:29.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,甲壳虫乐队什么的--每个人都很疯狂,\N{\rasEng}see the Beatles or something -- everybody was crazy,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.39,0:17:31.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在物理研讨会中\N{\rasEng}and there was spontaneous applause
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.16,0:17:32.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,人们都会自发的鼓掌,\N{\rasEng}at a physics seminar,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.43,0:17:33.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这种情况从未发生过,你知道吗,\N{\rasEng}which never happens,you know？
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.39,0:17:34.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就像是等了几十年之后\N{\rasEng}It's like seeing the Beatles
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.36,0:17:35.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,才能看到甲壳虫乐队的音乐会一样.\N{\rasEng}after waiting for it for decades.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.96,0:17:37.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,对,是的.正是.\N{\rasEng}Right,right. Exactly.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.40,0:17:39.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Evans：我希望这不是结束,\N{\rasEng}Evans: It's,I hope,not the end,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.13,0:17:41.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这只是漫漫长路的一小步,\N{\rasEng}but it is a little step in a long journey.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.37,0:17:43.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们花了40年才走到这一步,\N{\rasEng}It's taken us 40 years to get here.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.67,0:17:46.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不过我们现在向着我们对自然的了解\N{\rasEng}And we now have a marvelous step forward
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.11,0:17:48.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,走了了不起的一步.\N{\rasEng}in our understanding of nature.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.48,0:17:50.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela:希格斯场和我们\N{\rasEng}Incandela: The Higgs field is unlike
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.81,0:17:52.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,之前见过的都不一样.\N{\rasEng}anything we've ever seen before.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.71,0:17:54.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯场是我们无论去哪都要\N{\rasEng}The Higgs field is part of this fabric
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.85,0:17:57.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,与之相互作用的结构的一部分.\N{\rasEng}that we're interacting with everywhere we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.25,0:17:59.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,从这个角度,某种程度上我们\N{\rasEng}From it,we can,to some extent,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.19,0:18:02.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,甚至可能去了解宇宙的进化.\N{\rasEng}even possibly understand the evolution of the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.26,0:18:05.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这是个意义深远的发现.\N{\rasEng}It's a very profound finding.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.73,0:18:10.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：这次发现被称为继爱因斯坦写下\N{\rasEng}Freeman: It's being called the greatest scientific discovery
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.66,0:18:14.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,质能方程后的最大的科学发现.\N{\rasEng}since Einstein wrote "e=mc squared."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.44,0:18:17.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incandela: 一个伟大的艺术品正是那些,\N{\rasEng}Incandela: A great piece of art is something that,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.47,0:18:18.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可以永远存留的.\N{\rasEng}you know,lasts forever.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.81,0:18:22.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个新的科学发现或发展\N{\rasEng}A new scientific discovery or development
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.88,0:18:26.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,对人类进步的贡献是永久的.\N{\rasEng}is something that contributes to humanity for all time.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.08,0:18:30.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：这个粒子可以解释\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The particle that could solve the riddle of our existence
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.38,0:18:33.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们的存在之谜.\N{\rasEng}has been spotted.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.02,0:18:37.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么我们接近了了解宇宙的最后一步么？\N{\rasEng}Are we closing in on a final understanding of the universe？
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.49,0:18:40.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Dan Hooper认为答案可能会更加复杂,\N{\rasEng}Dan Hooper thinks the answer may be more complicated,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.93,0:18:44.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可能并不只有一种希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}that there may not be one Higgs boson
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.53,0:18:47.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而是有五种.\N{\rasEng}but five.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.71,0:18:54.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：人们认为希格斯玻色子可以解释\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The Higgs boson is supposed to explain
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.58,0:18:59.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙中所有物质的来源.\N{\rasEng}where all the matter in the universe came from.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.08,0:19:01.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但在过去十年中,我们得知\N{\rasEng}But in the last decade,we've learned that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.28,0:19:03.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙中大部分是由\N{\rasEng}most of our universe is made up of
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.15,0:19:07.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,称作暗物质的看不见的粒子组成.\N{\rasEng}invisible particles called dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.82,0:19:11.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,实际上暗物质比普通物质\N{\rasEng}In fact,there is five times more dark matter
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.23,0:19:13.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,多出了5倍.\N{\rasEng}than ordinary matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.86,0:19:18.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,现有理论预测希格斯玻色子的存在\N{\rasEng}The current theory that predicts the existence of the Higgs boson
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.30,0:19:23.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,无法解释这些奇特物质的存在.\N{\rasEng}offers no explanation for this strange substance.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.31,0:19:28.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那希格斯玻色子具有隐藏的阴暗面么？\N{\rasEng}Could the Higgs have a hidden dark side？
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.55,0:19:32.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,理论物理学家Dan Hooper\N{\rasEng}Theoretical physicist Dan Hooper
Dialogue: 0,0:19:32.48,0:19:34.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,用去了他整个职业生涯在等待\N{\rasEng}has been waiting his whole career
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.72,0:19:36.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}for the announcement that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.05,0:19:39.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,的发现.\N{\rasEng}the Higgs boson has been discovered.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:39.22,0:19:43.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hooper：我一直在我的电脑上\N{\rasEng}Hooper: I was up streaming it on my laptop,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.16,0:19:45.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,热切地等待结果.\N{\rasEng}enthusiastically waiting for the results.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.26,0:19:47.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你等待某些东西如此之久,\N{\rasEng}You wait for something this long,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.10,0:19:48.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当你等到的时候,\N{\rasEng}and when it happens,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.90,0:19:52.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不论你认为自己准备的多么充分,\N{\rasEng}no matter how prepared you think you should be for it to happen,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.23,0:19:54.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都仍会感到离奇,\N{\rasEng}it seems surreal.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.57,0:19:56.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,仍会觉得意外,\N{\rasEng}It seems unexpected
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.21,0:19:58.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不论之前如何的期待结果.\N{\rasEng}no matter how expected it should have been.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.44,0:20:03.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：希格斯玻色子被发现了.\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The Higgs has been found.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.75,0:20:07.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是一个大谜团仍然存在,\N{\rasEng}But a huge mystery still remains.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.35,0:20:10.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,暗物质是什么？\N{\rasEng}What is dark matter？
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.75,0:20:13.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hooper：宇宙学的一个最大问题,\N{\rasEng}Hooper: One of the biggest problems in cosmology
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.52,0:20:16.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就是当我们用望远镜观看远方,\N{\rasEng}is that when we look in telescopes at space,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.16,0:20:18.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们发现只能看到物质总量中\N{\rasEng}we find that only a small fraction of the total matter
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.69,0:20:21.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,由像原子和其他已知物质组成的一小部分.\N{\rasEng}is made up of things like atoms and other known material.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.33,0:20:23.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,其中的大部分都是一类幻影物质,\N{\rasEng}Most of it is some sort of elusive material
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.43,0:20:26.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,由于缺乏一个更好的名字,我们称之为暗物质.\N{\rasEng}that,for lack of a better name,we just call dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.77,0:20:31.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：半个世纪以来,对亚原子世界的探索\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Half a century of exploring the subatomic world
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.04,0:20:33.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,揭示了一个组织结构,\N{\rasEng}has revealed an organizing structure
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.41,0:20:37.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,被称作“粒子物理标准模型”.\N{\rasEng}called the standard model of particle physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.71,0:20:41.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家发现了物质的12种基本粒子,\N{\rasEng}Scientists have discovered 12 fundamental particles of matter,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.58,0:20:45.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,费米子,均分在夸克和轻子中.\N{\rasEng}the fermions,equally split among quarks and leptons.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.59,0:20:48.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,有四种粒子传播力,\N{\rasEng}There are four particles that transmit force
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.22,0:20:50.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如电和磁.\N{\rasEng}like electricity and magnetism.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.76,0:20:52.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些都是玻色子.\N{\rasEng}These are the bosons.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.96,0:20:55.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,接下来完成这幅图的是\N{\rasEng}And then,completing the picture,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.30,0:20:59.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个非常奇特的玻色子,希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}is one very special boson,the Higgs boson.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.67,0:21:04.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是标准模型并没有解释暗物质.\N{\rasEng}But the standard model has no explanation for dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.87,0:21:08.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另外还有一个严重的缺陷,\N{\rasEng}And it has another serious flaw.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.74,0:21:11.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,粒子物理标准模型\N{\rasEng}One of the biggest problems with
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.18,0:21:12.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,其中一个最大的问题\N{\rasEng}the standard model of particle physics
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.58,0:21:14.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就是所谓的“级列问题”.\N{\rasEng}is something we call the hierarchy problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.28,0:21:16.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们知道希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}We know that the Higgs boson
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.05,0:21:18.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,质量大约有126兆电子伏\N{\rasEng}has a mass of about 126 giga-electron volts
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.92,0:21:19.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,或简称gev.\N{\rasEng}or gev.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.96,0:21:22.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这是一个非常重的粒子,但是我们天真地\N{\rasEng}This is a heavy particle,but naively,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.59,0:21:24.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,根据标准模型预想\N{\rasEng}we'd expect,according to the standard model,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.56,0:21:27.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子会比这个还要重很多.\N{\rasEng}that the Higgs should be much,much heavier than this.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.03,0:21:28.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但由于某种原因,它的质量很小.\N{\rasEng}And for some reason,it's lighter.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.86,0:21:34.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：希格斯玻色子有着重量问题.\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The Higgs has weight issues.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.04,0:21:37.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如希格斯玻色子会把质量分给其他粒子,\N{\rasEng}Just as the Higgs boson gives mass to other particles,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.11,0:21:38.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而其他的粒子会轮流\N{\rasEng}other particles,in turn,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.64,0:21:41.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,给希格斯玻色子质量.\N{\rasEng}contribute to the mass of the Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.04,0:21:44.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当物理学家计算希格斯玻色子可以\N{\rasEng}When physicists work out how big the Higgs should get
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.65,0:21:47.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,从其他粒子那里获得多少质量,他们的结果表明其重量\N{\rasEng}from these other particles,they come up with a weight
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.52,0:21:50.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,会比其本身重数十亿倍.\N{\rasEng}billions of times heavier than it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.99,0:21:53.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家们只能敷衍这个数学问题\N{\rasEng}Scientists have had to fudge the math
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.19,0:21:55.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来创立标准模型.\N{\rasEng}to make the standard model work,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.52,0:21:59.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,虽然他们知道有些东西错过了.\N{\rasEng}fully knowing something is off.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.33,0:22:00.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hooper：为了解释这个问题,\N{\rasEng}Hooper: So,to explain this,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.96,0:22:04.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,有些东西需要非常精确的互相抵消,\N{\rasEng}something has to very precisely cancel one another
Dialogue: 0,0:22:04.93,0:22:08.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,使希格斯玻色子的质量恢复到观测值.\N{\rasEng}to restore the Higgs mass to its observed value.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.24,0:22:11.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[演奏蓝调音乐]\N{\rasEng}[ Blues music plays ]
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.57,0:22:15.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：当希格斯玻色子和暗物质给Dan施加了太大压力时,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: When the Higgs and dark matter weigh too heavily on Dan,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:15.18,0:22:18.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他就抽身于物理放松精神.\N{\rasEng}he takes a mental break from physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.45,0:22:24.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,研究暗物质的他和他的叫做Congregation的乐队,\N{\rasEng}The only dark matter he and his band,the Congregation,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.42,0:22:27.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,演唱的则是受伤的心.\N{\rasEng}sing about are broken hearts.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.82,0:22:32.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而Dan却发现音乐规则\N{\rasEng}But Dan can't help but find parallels
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.76,0:22:36.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,和宇宙的规则有相通之处.\N{\rasEng}between the rules of music and the rules of the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.83,0:22:38.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[音乐结束]\N{\rasEng}[ Song ends ]
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.87,0:22:41.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,很有趣的是许多我知道的物理学家\N{\rasEng}It's amazing how many physicists I know
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.77,0:22:44.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,也都是老练的音乐家,\N{\rasEng}who are also accomplished musicians,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.04,0:22:46.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,也许这之间是有关联的.\N{\rasEng}and maybe there's reasons for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.07,0:22:48.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你在粒子物理中发现的规律\N{\rasEng}The patterns that you find in particle physics
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.61,0:22:50.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,常常和音乐理论中的规律\N{\rasEng}are oftentimes pretty similar to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.31,0:22:52.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,有着非常相似的对称性.\N{\rasEng}the kind of symmetries you can find in music theory.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.25,0:22:56.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[演奏蓝调音乐]\N{\rasEng}[ Blues music plays ]
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.45,0:22:58.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼:Dan认为自然界中存在某种规律\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Dan believes there is a pattern in nature
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.95,0:23:01.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可以解释希格斯玻色子较小的质量\N{\rasEng}that can solve the small mass of the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.79,0:23:04.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,以及暗物质.\N{\rasEng}and explain dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.33,0:23:07.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这正是一种对标准模型的修饰,\N{\rasEng}It is an idea that modifies the standard model.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.33,0:23:10.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,称作“超对称”(费米子与玻色子之间的对称性).\N{\rasEng}It's called supersymmetry.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.50,0:23:15.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,♪ ...looking for so long\N{\rasEng}♪ ...looking for so long
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.50,0:23:20.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,♪ but each time that I've tried ♪\N{\rasEng}♪ but each time that I've tried ♪
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.21,0:23:22.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hooper:对于每块物质,\N{\rasEng}Hooper: For every piece of matter,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.31,0:23:24.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,每种费米粒子来说,\N{\rasEng}every kind of fermionic particle,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.38,0:23:26.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都要有一个玻色子粒子\N{\rasEng}there has to be a bosonic particle,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.01,0:23:27.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,作为力的载体.\N{\rasEng}a force carrier.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.05,0:23:28.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,光子需要光微子,\N{\rasEng}So,the photon requires a photino,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.72,0:23:30.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,电子需要Selectron【找不到翻译呢...】.\N{\rasEng}the electron a selectron.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.05,0:23:31.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在音乐理论中,\N{\rasEng}In music theory,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.35,0:23:34.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果你弹奏大调音阶,比如C大调音阶...\N{\rasEng}if you have a major scale like this "C" major scale...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.82,0:23:38.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[演奏音阶]\N{\rasEng}[ Scale plays ]
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.93,0:23:42.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...而同样的音符通过不同的排序演奏\N{\rasEng}...those same notes have to make up an "A" minor scale
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.33,0:23:44.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就是A小调音阶.\N{\rasEng}if you just play them in a different order.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.07,0:23:47.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[演奏音阶]\N{\rasEng}[ Scale plays ]
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.34,0:23:48.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么在一个超对称世界中,\N{\rasEng}So,in a supersymmetric world,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.90,0:23:51.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你不能只有光子而没有光微子,\N{\rasEng}you can't have a photon without a photino,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.64,0:23:53.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而在音乐理论中,\N{\rasEng}and in our music theory,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.38,0:23:56.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不能只有大调音阶而没有小调音阶.\N{\rasEng}you can't have a major scale without a minor scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:56.28,0:23:58.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：根据超对称原理,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: According to supersymmetry,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.95,0:24:01.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们观测到的粒子\N{\rasEng}the particles we have observed in nature
Dialogue: 0,0:24:01.62,0:24:04.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,仅仅是整个图景中的一半.\N{\rasEng}are only half of the picture.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.75,0:24:09.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一定互相存在大量的超对称粒子.\N{\rasEng}There must be massive superpartners for each one.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.59,0:24:14.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些超对称粒子中的一种可能就是暗物质.\N{\rasEng}One of these superpartners might even be dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.20,0:24:16.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么在大多数超对称理论中,\N{\rasEng}So,in most supersymmetric theories,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.43,0:24:19.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,最轻的新粒子会是\N{\rasEng}the lightest of the new particles you introduce
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.03,0:24:21.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,暗物质的最佳候选者.\N{\rasEng}is a very nice candidate for dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.34,0:24:24.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在早期宇宙,还是非常热的时候,\N{\rasEng}So,in the early universe,when the universe was very hot,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.17,0:24:27.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些粒子的数量极为丰富,\N{\rasEng}these particles would have been produced in copious numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.04,0:24:29.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但大多数都会被毁掉,只有一点点会存留下来,\N{\rasEng}Most of it would get destroyed,but a little bit would survive,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.68,0:24:31.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,留下来的一点点可能形成了\N{\rasEng}and that little bit could make up
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.18,0:24:33.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,今日宇宙中的暗物质.\N{\rasEng}all of the dark matter in our universe today.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.02,0:24:39.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：根据Dan的理论,如果对称是\N{\rasEng}Freeman: According to Dan,if symmetries
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.76,0:24:42.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们宇宙的基本部分,\N{\rasEng}are a fundamental part of our universe,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.69,0:24:46.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们就能够找到希格斯玻色子真正的质量.\N{\rasEng}they can set the Higgs at the correct mass.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.03,0:24:47.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hooper：如果超对称的确存在,\N{\rasEng}Hooper: If supersymmetry exists in nature,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.86,0:24:49.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么每次得到一个粒子,\N{\rasEng}then every contribution given
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.90,0:24:51.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如说一个电子,\N{\rasEng}from a particle,like an electron,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.77,0:24:53.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就会又得到一个与之相反的\N{\rasEng}gets an opposite contribution
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.80,0:24:55.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,超对称粒子Selectron,\N{\rasEng}from its superpartner,the selectron,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.57,0:24:56.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样它们是平衡的.\N{\rasEng}and they balance.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.77,0:24:58.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们在大部分地方都互相抵消,\N{\rasEng}They cancel each other out for the most part,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.37,0:25:01.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,留给我的是非常轻的希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}leaving us with a pretty light Higgs boson.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:03.44,0:25:05.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：超对称解释了\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Supersymmetry makes sense
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.15,0:25:06.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,标准模型无法解释的现象.\N{\rasEng}where the standard model does not.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.85,0:25:10.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就可以解释小质量的希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}It can explain the small mass of the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.49,0:25:13.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,以及什么是暗物质.\N{\rasEng}and what dark matter is.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.36,0:25:16.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这是这里有个陷阱,\N{\rasEng}But there is a catch.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.53,0:25:19.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,为了使超对称理论为真,\N{\rasEng}In order for supersymmetry to be true,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.53,0:25:22.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就还需要不仅一种希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}there has to be not just one Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.43,0:25:24.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而是5种.\N{\rasEng}but five.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.50,0:25:26.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果自然界真的具有超对称性质,\N{\rasEng}If nature really is supersymmetric
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.67,0:25:28.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而且只有一种希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}and there were only one Higgs boson,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.40,0:25:29.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这个理论就会存在\N{\rasEng}the theory would contain
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.81,0:25:32.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们称为“反常”的数学问题.\N{\rasEng}mathematical problems we call anomalies.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.04,0:25:34.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就会存在许多悖论.\N{\rasEng}It would contain paradoxes.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.38,0:25:37.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,为了解决这些问题,就需要引入额外的希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}And to solve this,you need to introduce extra Higgs bosons.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.91,0:25:40.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果CERN能够发现第二个或第三个\N{\rasEng}If CERN were to discover a second or third
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.22,0:25:42.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,甚至第四个第五个希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}or fourth or fifth Higgs boson,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.02,0:25:44.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就可以有力的增加超对称的例子,\N{\rasEng}it would strengthen the case for supersymmetry,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.09,0:25:45.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,甚至我们不需要亲眼\N{\rasEng}even if we hadn't observed
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.29,0:25:48.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,观测到这些超对称粒子本身.\N{\rasEng}those superparticle partners themselves yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.19,0:25:51.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果要解释\N{\rasEng}If we are to explain the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:25:51.29,0:25:53.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们已知的宇宙,\N{\rasEng}as we already know it,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.30,0:25:58.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,去了解暗物质如何会伴随着一般物质,\N{\rasEng}to understand how dark matter lives alongside ordinary matter,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.50,0:26:03.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家还要再发现五种希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}scientists need to find evidence for five Higgs bosons.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.97,0:26:09.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,花了40年才发现一个上帝粒子,\N{\rasEng}It took 40 years to find one God particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.44,0:26:13.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们注定会错过终极真理吗？\N{\rasEng}Is the ultimate truth destined to elude us？
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.47,0:26:18.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子担负着\N{\rasEng}The Higgs boson is responsible for
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.44,0:26:22.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,解释全宇宙物质来源的重任.\N{\rasEng}giving everything in the entire universe mass.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.15,0:26:25.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这对于一个亚原子粒子来说 是一个很重大的工作.\N{\rasEng}That's a big job for one subatomic particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.88,0:26:29.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一些科学家认为这对于一个粒子来说过于重大了.\N{\rasEng}Some scientists believe it's too big a job for one particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.89,0:26:32.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果上帝粒子本身\N{\rasEng}What if the God particle
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.19,0:26:35.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不会自身携带重量呢？\N{\rasEng}isn't carrying the weight all by itself？
Dialogue: 0,0:26:35.63,0:26:37.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,或许宇宙的真正设计\N{\rasEng}Perhaps the real design of the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.93,0:26:41.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,需要多于一种希格斯玻色子扮演上帝.\N{\rasEng}needs more than one Higgs to play God.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.03,0:26:47.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,John Ellis是CERN的一个理论物理学家,\N{\rasEng}John Ellis is a theoretical physicist at CERN.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.77,0:26:50.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他一直在花时间出主意,\N{\rasEng}He spends his time thinking up ideas,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.57,0:26:55.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,很多主意在实验中常被证明错误.\N{\rasEng}ideas that experiments here often prove wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.11,0:26:57.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但这对于John来说还好.\N{\rasEng}But that's okay by John.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.28,0:26:59.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ellis: 那么我的工作就是\N{\rasEng}Ellis: So,no,my job is to
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.92,0:27:01.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,为实验要寻找的对象提供想法,\N{\rasEng}think of things for the experiments to look for,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.52,0:27:03.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后,就像我常说的,\N{\rasEng}and then,as I like to say,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.35,0:27:05.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我希望他们能发现一些不同的东西.\N{\rasEng}I hope they find something different.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.29,0:27:09.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Albert de Roeck是位实验物理学家,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Albert de Roeck is an experimental physicist.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.83,0:27:13.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他则花时间检验主意,\N{\rasEng}He spends his time testing ideas,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:13.63,0:27:15.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希望能够证明它们是错误的.\N{\rasEng}hoping to prove them wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.67,0:27:20.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我加入这些实验希望能够找到\N{\rasEng}I joined these experiments in pursuit of
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.10,0:27:23.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,打破标准模型的东西,\N{\rasEng}finding something to crack the standard model,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.17,0:27:25.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,通过找到超出标准模型之外的东西\N{\rasEng}possibly kill the standard model
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.24,0:27:27.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,将其扼杀掉.\N{\rasEng}by finding things beyond the standard model.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.71,0:27:31.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Albert,实验者,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Albert,the experimentalist,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:31.11,0:27:32.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,John,思考者,\N{\rasEng}and John,the thinker,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.75,0:27:35.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,自从开始就同时都成为了\N{\rasEng}have both been part of the hunt for the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.18,0:27:37.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,寻找希格斯玻色子的组成部分,\N{\rasEng}since the beginning.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.45,0:27:42.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子起初设想用来解决一个谜题--\N{\rasEng}The Higgs boson was originally supposed to solve one mystery --
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.66,0:27:46.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,“w”和“z”玻色子的质量,【w、z玻色子：弱相互作用的承载粒子】\N{\rasEng}the mass of the "w" and "z" bosons,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.56,0:27:49.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们都非常之重.\N{\rasEng}which are extremely heavy.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.20,0:27:53.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另两种玻色子基本没有质量.\N{\rasEng}The other two bosons are massless.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.47,0:27:57.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学家认为“w”和“z”玻色子非常的重\N{\rasEng}Physicists proposed the "w" and "z" get heavy
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.37,0:27:59.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是因为它们都单独与\N{\rasEng}because they alone interact with
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.71,0:28:03.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,无处不在的看不见的力场--\N{\rasEng}an invisible field that is everywhere --
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.01,0:28:04.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯场相互作用.\N{\rasEng}the Higgs field.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.95,0:28:08.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是其他的玻色子不这样.\N{\rasEng}But the other bosons do not.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:08.05,0:28:11.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,随后,当标准模型写出后,\N{\rasEng}Later,when the standard model was written,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:11.42,0:28:14.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯场的概念就被延伸到\N{\rasEng}the idea of the Higgs field was extended
Dialogue: 0,0:28:14.06,0:28:16.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个更为重大的工作上--\N{\rasEng}to take on a much bigger job --
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.59,0:28:20.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,赋予整个宇宙质量.\N{\rasEng}to give mass to the entire universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.86,0:28:22.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这是一类附加的东西,\N{\rasEng}It was sort of added on.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.23,0:28:26.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不是这种机制发明的原因.\N{\rasEng}It was not why this mechanism was invented.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.17,0:28:29.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：但是像Albert和John这类的物理学家知道\N{\rasEng}Freeman: But physicists like Albert and John know
Dialogue: 0,0:28:29.91,0:28:32.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这个粒子可能并不能担负起\N{\rasEng}this one particle may not be responsible
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.64,0:28:35.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,赋予所有物质质量的重任.\N{\rasEng}for giving mass to everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.11,0:28:37.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ellis: 物理学中有大量的理论\N{\rasEng}Ellis: There's myriads of theories out there in physics
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.68,0:28:38.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都超出了标准模型,\N{\rasEng}beyond the standard model,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.88,0:28:40.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些理论具有的普遍特点是\N{\rasEng}and it's a general feature of them
Dialogue: 0,0:28:40.55,0:28:42.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们预测的东西比\N{\rasEng}that they predict something more complicated
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.99,0:28:44.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,单独的希格斯玻色子复杂得多.\N{\rasEng}than just a single Higgs boson.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.92,0:28:48.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼:John和Albert一直在尝试\N{\rasEng}Freeman: John and Albert have been trying to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.72,0:28:52.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,基于标准模型并同时修复其错误\N{\rasEng}come up with new theories,building upon the standard model
Dialogue: 0,0:28:52.36,0:28:55.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来想出一些新理论.\N{\rasEng}while fixing what is wrong with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.26,0:28:58.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这意味着他们必须改变他们对\N{\rasEng}It means they must change their predictions
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.60,0:29:01.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子到底是什么的预测.\N{\rasEng}for what the Higgs actually is.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.67,0:29:05.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,已经预测出了几种不同的\N{\rasEng}Several varieties of Higgs particles
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.01,0:29:06.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子.\N{\rasEng}have been predicted.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:06.48,0:29:09.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你可以想象是冰淇淋的不同口味.\N{\rasEng}You can think of it like flavors of ice cream.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.48,0:29:13.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果LHC发现的是纯的、过时的香草口味希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}If the LHC found a plain,old,vanilla Higgs,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.25,0:29:16.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就确认了物理学家已经知道的东西.\N{\rasEng}it confirms what physicists already know.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.45,0:29:19.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[唉]\N{\rasEng}[ Sighs ]
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.06,0:29:22.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是如果发现的是有更多让人兴奋的口味\N{\rasEng}But if it turns out to be a more exciting flavor
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.73,0:29:24.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如薄荷巧克力块口味,\N{\rasEng}like mint-chocolate-chip,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.79,0:29:28.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就为物理打开了新的令人兴奋的可能.\N{\rasEng}it opens up new thrilling possibilities for physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.97,0:29:31.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[拥抱亲吻]\N{\rasEng}[ Smooching ]
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.00,0:29:32.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,哦！\N{\rasEng}Oh!
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.04,0:29:36.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,其中一个可能就是\N{\rasEng}One of these possibilities would be that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.61,0:29:41.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,有两种希格斯玻色子,分别担任不同的工作.\N{\rasEng}there are two Higgs bosons,each with a different job.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.14,0:29:44.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,已经有了非常多的想法认为\N{\rasEng}So,there's been,you know,a number of ideas that say,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.01,0:29:47.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,“好吧,可能会发生一些外包的情况,”\N{\rasEng}"well,maybe there's a bit of outsourcing going on,"
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.48,0:29:49.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}and that there is one Higgs boson
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.35,0:29:50.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,负责“w”和“zed”玻色子,\N{\rasEng}for the "w" and the "zed"
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.72,0:29:53.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另一个则负责物质粒子.\N{\rasEng}and another one for the matter particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.26,0:29:58.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：可以想象John是“z”玻色子,力的载体,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Imagine John is a "z" boson,a force carrier.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.59,0:30:02.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Albert是个夸克,物质的载体.\N{\rasEng}Albert is a quark,a matter carrier.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:02.57,0:30:04.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,John是个总所周知的咖啡狂,\N{\rasEng}John is a well-known coffee addict.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:04.97,0:30:08.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Akbert是人们所知的巧克力狂,\N{\rasEng}Albert is a well-known chocoholic.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.70,0:30:11.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么把这个咖啡馆当做一个希格斯场,\N{\rasEng}Say this café is one Higgs field
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.91,0:30:14.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,巧克力店则是另一个.\N{\rasEng}and this chocolate shop is another.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.91,0:30:20.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当John经过咖啡馆,他会放慢脚步获得质量.\N{\rasEng}When John passes the café,he will slow down and gain mass.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.62,0:30:22.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,De Roeck: 但另一个粒子,我自己,\N{\rasEng}De Roeck: But the other particle,myself,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.42,0:30:24.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,会快速经过咖啡馆,\N{\rasEng}would just zap through until
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.02,0:30:27.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,直到我遇到了能与我作用的场,\N{\rasEng}I encounter the field with which I'm interacting,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.09,0:30:28.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就会给我质量--\N{\rasEng}and that would give me mass --
Dialogue: 0,0:30:28.56,0:30:30.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在这个例子中就是巧克力商店.\N{\rasEng}in this case,a chocolate shop.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.29,0:30:33.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：标准模型\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The standard model
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.03,0:30:36.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不包括两种希格斯场,\N{\rasEng}doesn't include two Higgs fields,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.07,0:30:40.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这也是这种想法能够吸引John和Albert的原因.\N{\rasEng}which is why this idea is so appealing to John and Albert.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.54,0:30:44.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果我们发现不仅有一种希格斯玻色子,（或说不仅有一种希格斯场）\N{\rasEng}If we were to find that there is more than one Higgs,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.24,0:30:46.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就意味着物理学\N{\rasEng}that would mean for sure
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.24,0:30:49.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,肯定超出了标准模型.\N{\rasEng}there is physics beyond the standard model.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.98,0:30:51.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ellis: 现在如果我们寻找的\N{\rasEng}Ellis: Now,if what we're looking at
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.65,0:30:53.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是并不十分精确的东西,\N{\rasEng}is something which is not exactly,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:53.25,0:30:55.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如你祖母的希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}you know,your grandmother's Higgs boson,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.05,0:30:58.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,某种方式来说确实让人很兴奋.\N{\rasEng}that could actually,in a way,be even more exciting.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.25,0:31:01.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼: 现在,当新发现的希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}Freeman: So far,there are some signs of anomalies
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.86,0:31:04.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,开始衰退时,表现出了反常的迹象,\N{\rasEng}in the way this new particle decays,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.59,0:31:07.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,表明会有其他种类的希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}suggesting an exotic flavor of the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.50,0:31:10.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,隐藏在数据之中.\N{\rasEng}might be lurking in the data.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.23,0:31:14.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,还仍有大量的数据等待分析.\N{\rasEng}And there are still piles of data waiting to be analyzed.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.60,0:31:18.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,De Roeck: 我真心希望这个希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}De Roeck: I actually hope that this Higgs boson
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.67,0:31:21.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是通往超出标准模型的\N{\rasEng}is gonna be a portal to the new physics
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.81,0:31:24.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,新的物理学的大门.\N{\rasEng}which we're going to find beyond the standard model.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.35,0:31:25.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这非常让人兴奋,\N{\rasEng}And that would be exciting because
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.82,0:31:28.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,因为每次这种事情的发生,我们就能够学到新东西.\N{\rasEng}each time that happens,we learn something new.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.12,0:31:31.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：LHC也暗示了\N{\rasEng}Freeman: The LHC may be hinting that
Dialogue: 0,0:31:31.45,0:31:34.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子只是众多扮演者中的一个,\N{\rasEng}the Higgs is only one of many players.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.72,0:31:38.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它不会全然就是上帝粒子.\N{\rasEng}It may not be the God particle after all.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.59,0:31:41.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这个人认为创造宇宙的真相\N{\rasEng}This man thinks the truth about the creation of the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:31:41.93,0:31:45.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比长久以来才发现的希格斯玻色子还要深远,\N{\rasEng}lies deeper than the long-sought Higgs,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.37,0:31:47.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们只是才刚开始想象\N{\rasEng}that we owe our existence to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.54,0:31:51.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子是我们存在的原因.\N{\rasEng}particles we have only just begun to imagine.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.11,0:31:56.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希腊哲学家德谟克利特,\N{\rasEng}It was the Greek philosopher Democritus
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.23,0:31:58.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,第一个提出了原子.\N{\rasEng}who first thought of the atom.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.90,0:32:00.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他认为原子是\N{\rasEng}He imagined it to be
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.53,0:32:04.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物质形成的最小单位,\N{\rasEng}the smallest possible building block of matter,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:04.20,0:32:06.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它不能再分了.\N{\rasEng}one that could never be divided.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.67,0:32:10.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他的想法成功延续了2000年,\N{\rasEng}His idea was good enough to last 2,000 years,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.64,0:32:15.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,直到核子时代的到来才揭示了更深层次的真相.\N{\rasEng}until the nuclear age came along and revealed a deeper truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.81,0:32:19.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,原子也是由更小的东西组成,\N{\rasEng}The atom is made up of smaller things.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.75,0:32:24.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比如夸克和电子组成了原子,\N{\rasEng}Just as particles like quarks and electrons make up the atom,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.25,0:32:27.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们是更小的,更基本的组成单位,\N{\rasEng}smaller,more fundamental building blocks
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.49,0:32:30.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而又可能由希格斯玻色子组成.\N{\rasEng}might make up the Higgs boson.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:30.26,0:32:33.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,如果我们发现它们,就不仅能揭示\N{\rasEng}If we can find them,they could reveal
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.80,0:32:38.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物质如何存在的,包括物质为什么存在.\N{\rasEng}not just how matter exists but why it came to be.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.07,0:32:46.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Francesco Sannino是位理论物理学家\N{\rasEng}Francesco Sannino is a theoretical physicist
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.64,0:32:51.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就职于欧登赛的南丹麦大学.\N{\rasEng}at the University of Southern Denmark in Odense.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.08,0:32:57.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他居住于能够让他的想象力狂野驰骋的完美城镇.\N{\rasEng}He lives in the perfect town to let his imagination run wild.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.02,0:32:58.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,欧登赛是著名儿童故事作家\N{\rasEng}Odense is the birthplace
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.79,0:33:01.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,汉斯·克里斯蒂安·安徒生\N{\rasEng}of the famous children's story author
Dialogue: 0,0:33:01.56,0:33:04.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,的出生地.\N{\rasEng}Hans Christian Andersen.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:04.63,0:33:07.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们就在安徒生居住地的附近,\N{\rasEng}So,we are in the Hans Christian Andersen neighborhood.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.83,0:33:09.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他在这里出生,\N{\rasEng}He was born here,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.00,0:33:12.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他描绘了很多这样的街道,\N{\rasEng}and he has drawn a lot from these streets.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:12.37,0:33:13.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像你看到的,\N{\rasEng}As you can see,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.70,0:33:18.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就像是故事书中的一页.\N{\rasEng}it looks like taken by a page from a storybook.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.14,0:33:21.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：但不同于这个童话般的小镇,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: But unlike this fairy-tale town,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.14,0:33:22.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们对于\N{\rasEng}our understanding
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.41,0:33:24.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙的基本组成单位的了解\N{\rasEng}of the fundamental building blocks of the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:33:24.51,0:33:26.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不是完美无缺的.\N{\rasEng}is not picture-perfect.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:26.62,0:33:28.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,标准模型\N{\rasEng}The standard model
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.25,0:33:32.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,认为希格斯玻色子是基本粒子,\N{\rasEng}regards the Higgs boson as a fundamental particle,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.49,0:33:35.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是Francesco的想象力驱使他看得更远,\N{\rasEng}but Francesco's imagination is driving him to look further,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.46,0:33:40.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,看他能否看到希格斯玻色子的内部.\N{\rasEng}to see if he can peer inside the Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.60,0:33:42.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sannino: 根据标准模型,\N{\rasEng}Sannino: According to the standard model,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.10,0:33:43.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子是一种基本粒子,\N{\rasEng}the Higgs is a fundamental particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:43.97,0:33:46.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这表明它不会被再分.\N{\rasEng}It means it's not made of something else.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.04,0:33:47.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么看这面墙,是白的.\N{\rasEng}So,look at this wall. It's white.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:47.97,0:33:50.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但实际上是有三种不同的光\N{\rasEng}But the truth is that there are three different lights
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.84,0:33:53.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,组合在一起显现出白色.\N{\rasEng}combined together making this white.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.11,0:33:54.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那么如果我把我手\N{\rasEng}In fact,see what happen
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.14,0:33:55.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,放在墙面前会发生什么.\N{\rasEng}if I put my hand in front of the wall.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:55.81,0:33:58.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我可以把它分解为三种不同的颜色,\N{\rasEng}I can resolve there's three different colors,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.85,0:34:01.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,绿、蓝、红,\N{\rasEng}the green,the blue,and the red.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.45,0:34:03.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们共同形成了白光.\N{\rasEng}Together,they form the white light.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.22,0:34:05.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：就像白光\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Just as a white light
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.09,0:34:07.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,实际上由三种不同颜色的光组成,\N{\rasEng}is actually made up of three different colors,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.99,0:34:10.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Francesco在想希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}Francesco wondered if the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:34:10.63,0:34:13.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是否由不同种类的粒子组成.\N{\rasEng}is made up of several different particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:13.30,0:34:14.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就说明了希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}This would mean the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.87,0:34:17.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不是所有物质存在的根基.\N{\rasEng}is not a fundamental root of all matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.53,0:34:19.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他和许多同事认为\N{\rasEng}He and many of his colleagues think
Dialogue: 0,0:34:19.94,0:34:23.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子自身就被一种新的自然力控制,\N{\rasEng}the Higgs itself is governed by a new force of nature,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.37,0:34:26.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们称这种力为人工色(力).\N{\rasEng}something they call the technicolor force.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:26.98,0:34:29.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sannino: 如果你要深入到希格斯玻色子内部,\N{\rasEng}Sannino: If you look deep inside the Higgs,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.11,0:34:31.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你会发现它由其他东西组成.\N{\rasEng}you will find it's made of something else.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.18,0:34:33.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,[钢琴演奏古典音乐] 【应该是肖邦圆舞曲】\N{\rasEng}[ Piano plays classical music ]
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.42,0:34:35.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Francesco认为\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Francesco believes
Dialogue: 0,0:34:35.52,0:34:39.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子用新节奏在跳舞.\N{\rasEng}the Higgs boson dances to a new tempo.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.62,0:34:42.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,把这些乐高玩具块当做普通夸克,\N{\rasEng}Imagine these Lego bricks are ordinary quarks
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.76,0:34:45.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这块板就是胶子代表的力（强核力）\N{\rasEng}and this board is the force of the gluons
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.70,0:34:47.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可以将它们组合在一起.\N{\rasEng}that holds them together.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.43,0:34:52.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,为了制作一个质子,我们要三个夸克.\N{\rasEng}To make a proton,we need three quarks.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.44,0:34:55.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,根据人工色原理,\N{\rasEng}According to the technicolor theory,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:55.04,0:34:56.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子都是一样的,\N{\rasEng}the Higgs is just the same,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:56.88,0:35:02.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是由不同种类的夸克组成--\N{\rasEng}but it is made up of different types of quarks --
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.05,0:35:04.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,techniquarks【这个怎么翻译呢...】.\N{\rasEng}techniquarks.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.28,0:35:07.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sannino: techniquarks由一种新的力\N{\rasEng}Sannino: The techniquarks are held together
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.82,0:35:10.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,组合在一起,就是人工色(力).\N{\rasEng}by a new force,a techniforce.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:10.75,0:35:13.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们相互作用产生的能量\N{\rasEng}And the energy that comes from the interactions
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.72,0:35:16.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,自发的为希格斯粒子提供质量.\N{\rasEng}also automatically provides the mass of the Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.86,0:35:18.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：物理学家知道\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Physicists know
Dialogue: 0,0:35:18.66,0:35:21.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,普通夸克的不同排列,\N{\rasEng}ordinary quarks in different arrangements
Dialogue: 0,0:35:21.73,0:35:23.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,创造了不同粒子.\N{\rasEng}make different particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.87,0:35:26.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一种排列是质子,\N{\rasEng}One arrangement is a proton.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.64,0:35:30.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另一种排列就是中子.\N{\rasEng}Another arrangement is a neutron.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.24,0:35:33.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Techniquarks的工作方式也相同,\N{\rasEng}Techniquarks work the same way.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.04,0:35:36.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一种方式排列,你就得到了希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}Arrange them one way,and you get a Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:36.81,0:35:39.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另将techniquarks用另一种方式排列,\N{\rasEng}But arrange those techniquarks another way,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:39.08,0:35:40.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你就会得到一些别的\N{\rasEng}and you get something else
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.42,0:35:42.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,科学家正在寻找的东西,\N{\rasEng}scientists have been looking for,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.25,0:35:45.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,暗物质粒子.\N{\rasEng}a dark-matter particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.59,0:35:48.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sannino: 这真的很像乐高玩具,\N{\rasEng}Sannino: So,it's really like a Lego brick.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.69,0:35:49.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,你把它们放在一起,\N{\rasEng}You put them together,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:49.93,0:35:51.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一种形式你得到了希格斯玻色子,\N{\rasEng}and in one form,you get the Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:51.93,0:35:55.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,另一种形式你能得到暗物质.\N{\rasEng}And in another form,you can get the dark matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.07,0:35:59.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：或许标准模型中希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Perhaps the reason the standard-model Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.00,0:36:00.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不能解释暗物质的原因\N{\rasEng}can't explain dark matter
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.94,0:36:05.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是因为希格斯玻色子是变相的暗物质,\N{\rasEng}is because the Higgs is dark matter in disguise
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.94,0:36:09.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不同形式的粒子的结合则通过\N{\rasEng}and both particles are held together
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.65,0:36:12.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,人工色(力).\N{\rasEng}by the techniforce.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:12.95,0:36:16.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这将会是一种新的自然力,\N{\rasEng}There will be definitely a new force of nature,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.32,0:36:19.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这对于人类来说是一个奇妙的机遇\N{\rasEng}so it will be fantastic opportunity for mankind
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.56,0:36:20.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来面对一个新的力.\N{\rasEng}to face a new force.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:20.99,0:36:25.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Techniquarks可以通过多种方式结合起来,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Techniquarks could be glued together in many ways,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.20,0:36:28.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,创造出几种新式粒子.\N{\rasEng}constructing several brand-new particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.27,0:36:32.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些粒子还正等待LHC的发现,\N{\rasEng}Those particles could be waiting to be discovered at the LHC
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.67,0:36:38.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,不过这要等到2015年重新以更高能量启动后了.\N{\rasEng}when it comes back online at much higher energies in 2015.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.14,0:36:41.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Francesco希望最近发现的希格斯玻色子\N{\rasEng}Francesco hopes that the Higgs boson recently discovered
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.78,0:36:43.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是第一候选者.\N{\rasEng}is the first candidate.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.51,0:36:45.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们总会一无所知,\N{\rasEng}We just won't know it
Dialogue: 0,0:36:45.15,0:36:48.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,直到我们有足够的力量将其撞开.\N{\rasEng}until we have enough power to crack it open.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.29,0:36:50.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sannino: 我觉得这是人类的责任\N{\rasEng}Sannino: I think it's the duty of human beings
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.09,0:36:52.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来了解什么在我身边以及什么造就了我们.\N{\rasEng}to understand what is around us and what makes us.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.92,0:36:55.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我认为这的确是一个很神奇的机遇\N{\rasEng}I think this is really a fantastic opportunity
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.56,0:36:58.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,来把科学的边界推到如此程度.\N{\rasEng}to push the boundaries of science to that degree.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.73,0:37:01.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼: 那么所谓的上帝粒子\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Does the so-called God particle
Dialogue: 0,0:37:01.97,0:37:04.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,真的有多个方面吗？\N{\rasEng}have multiple faces？
Dialogue: 0,0:37:04.40,0:37:08.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,或许希格斯玻色子并没有我们认为的那么万能.\N{\rasEng}Perhaps the Higgs is not as almighty as we thought.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.21,0:37:11.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们还有更多的离奇古怪的想法,\N{\rasEng}But there are much more mind-bending ideas.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:11.34,0:37:12.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,或许让我们存在的东西\N{\rasEng}What makes us exist
Dialogue: 0,0:37:12.91,0:37:17.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可能完全就不存在.\N{\rasEng}could be objects that don't really exist at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.71,0:37:22.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当我们仰望夜空,\N{\rasEng}When we look up at the night sky,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:22.58,0:37:24.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,月亮凝视着我们,\N{\rasEng}our moon peers down at us.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.72,0:37:28.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它似乎神奇的悬挂在稀薄的空气中,\N{\rasEng}It seem to be magically suspended in thin air,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:28.36,0:37:31.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,即使我们知道它是由重力\N{\rasEng}even though we know it's being held in place
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.86,0:37:33.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,保持在天空中的.\N{\rasEng}by the force of gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.80,0:37:36.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,那如果宇宙中所有的物质\N{\rasEng}What if all matter in the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:37:36.33,0:37:39.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都被一些别的东西锚定在那里呢,\N{\rasEng}is actually being anchored by something else,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.53,0:37:43.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一些比重力更陌生\N{\rasEng}something far stranger than gravity
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.14,0:37:46.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,比上帝粒子更奇异的东西？\N{\rasEng}and far stranger than the God particle？
Dialogue: 0,0:37:49.08,0:37:52.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,哈佛大学的Howard Georgi的\N{\rasEng}Howard Georgi from Harvard University
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.31,0:37:56.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,大半生都是一名粒子物理学家.\N{\rasEng}has been a particle physicist for most of his life.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.52,0:38:00.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是最近,他的事业发生了转变,\N{\rasEng}But recently,he has made a career change.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.22,0:38:04.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他现在是一位非粒子物理学家.\N{\rasEng}He is now an unparticle physicist.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:04.59,0:38:07.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我一直试图思考\N{\rasEng}I was trying to think about
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.36,0:38:11.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在LHC中得到的结果其实是很不同寻常的,\N{\rasEng}what the LHC might see that was really unusual,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.00,0:38:15.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我想到是否LHC中\N{\rasEng}and it occurred to me that whether there was something
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.10,0:38:19.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,表现出来的完全不是粒子.\N{\rasEng}that might show up at the LHC that was not particles at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.61,0:38:21.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就是我作为非粒子物理学家\N{\rasEng}That was the beginning of my career
Dialogue: 0,0:38:21.98,0:38:23.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,为事业的开端.\N{\rasEng}as an unparticle physicist.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.68,0:38:25.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：就像很多物理学家一样,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Like many physicists,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:25.48,0:38:28.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Howard一直在修正标准模型,\N{\rasEng}Howard has been trying to fix the standard model
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.45,0:38:30.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并创立一些新理论.\N{\rasEng}and come up with new theories.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.25,0:38:32.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当他正在计算他的等式时,\N{\rasEng}While working on his equations,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.62,0:38:36.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他注意到了一些让人茫然的计算.\N{\rasEng}he noticed some puzzling calculations.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:36.46,0:38:40.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学中,像光子这样无质量的粒子\N{\rasEng}In physics,massless particles like photons
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.70,0:38:43.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,在数学中以负整数表现.\N{\rasEng}show up in math as negative whole numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:43.60,0:38:47.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Howard从他的等式中得到的负数,\N{\rasEng}Howard's equations were giving him negative numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.10,0:38:49.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是它们不是整数.\N{\rasEng}but they weren't whole numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.44,0:38:53.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们只是负分数.\N{\rasEng}They were negative fractions.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.07,0:38:55.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Georgi: 你这样分析,\N{\rasEng}Georgi: You do this analysis,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.04,0:38:58.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就会得到2又1/2的无质量粒子,\N{\rasEng}and you might get 2 1/2 massless particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.71,0:39:01.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后,你抓着头说,\N{\rasEng}And then,you scratch your head and say,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:01.35,0:39:02.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,“什么？发生了什么？”\N{\rasEng}"What？ What is going on？"
Dialogue: 0,0:39:02.95,0:39:05.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼: Howard知道这些一半的分数\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Howard knew these half numbers
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.12,0:39:06.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并不代表半个粒子.\N{\rasEng}weren't half particles.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:06.39,0:39:11.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它们是一些新的东西,他称之为非粒子.\N{\rasEng}They were something new. He called them unparticles.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:11.09,0:39:12.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Georgi: 有些事正在发生,\N{\rasEng}Georgi: There's something happening.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:12.89,0:39:14.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,是一些物理学上的事,\N{\rasEng}There's some physics,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:14.16,0:39:19.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但又不是我们现在所用的物理学.\N{\rasEng}but it's not the sort of physics that we're used to.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:21.00,0:39:23.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：Howard进行了更深入的数学计算,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Howard probed the math deeper
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.20,0:39:25.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,更多的了解非粒子.\N{\rasEng}and learned more about unparticles.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:25.27,0:39:30.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他意识到出现分数的原因\N{\rasEng}He realized the reason they came out as fractions
Dialogue: 0,0:39:30.24,0:39:32.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,可能是由于分形维数,\N{\rasEng}is because they have fractal dimensions,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.35,0:39:35.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就像是一棵树的分枝.\N{\rasEng}much like the branches of a tree.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:35.28,0:39:37.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Georgi: 如果你看一棵树,\N{\rasEng}Georgi: If you look at the tree,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:37.29,0:39:39.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,它不是只有一个维数,\N{\rasEng}it's not one-dimensional,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:39.19,0:39:41.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,因为它长出了很多树枝,\N{\rasEng}because the tree comes and it branches,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:41.26,0:39:43.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后这些树枝再分枝.\N{\rasEng}and then the branches branch again.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:43.86,0:39:45.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样分枝之后再分枝,\N{\rasEng}And the branch's branches branch again.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:45.79,0:39:48.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,接着再分枝后再分枝,等等.\N{\rasEng}And the branch's branch's branches,et cetera and so on.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:48.60,0:39:50.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个真正分形中,这会永远进行下去.\N{\rasEng}In a true fractal,that would go on forever.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.93,0:39:54.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：非粒子就像这棵树的分枝.\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Unparticles are like the branches of this tree.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:54.94,0:39:56.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这些图形模式都是相同的,\N{\rasEng}The pattern is the same
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.64,0:40:00.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,无论你离得多么近或者多么远来看.\N{\rasEng}no matter how close or how far away you look.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:00.11,0:40:04.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但是一般粒子就像树叶,\N{\rasEng}But normal particles are like the leaves on the tree.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.38,0:40:09.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,离得越近看它,它就越大.\N{\rasEng}The closer you get,the bigger they look.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:09.08,0:40:12.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Georgi: 我喜欢这种把树叶当做\N{\rasEng}Georgi: I like the idea of thinking of the leaves
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.69,0:40:14.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,标准模型中的东西的想法,\N{\rasEng}as the objects of the standard model
Dialogue: 0,0:40:14.09,0:40:16.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,因为它们都有确定的大小,\N{\rasEng}because they have a definite size,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.39,0:40:18.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,正如一个粒子所具有的质量,\N{\rasEng}like a mass that a particle has,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:18.39,0:40:23.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而树的分枝却没有确定的大小.\N{\rasEng}whereas the branches of the tree don't have a definite size.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:23.00,0:40:26.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼: 构成宇宙的所有的粒子\N{\rasEng}Freeman: All of the particles that make up our universe
Dialogue: 0,0:40:26.40,0:40:27.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都有质量,\N{\rasEng}have mass,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:27.97,0:40:31.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,由于希格斯玻色子,物理学家相信质量的存在.\N{\rasEng}which physicists believe exists because of the Higgs.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:31.54,0:40:34.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但如果希格斯玻色子内部的粒子\N{\rasEng}But perhaps those particles in the Higgs
Dialogue: 0,0:40:34.31,0:40:38.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,实际上受限于看不见的非粒子世界,\N{\rasEng}are really being governed by an invisible world of unparticles
Dialogue: 0,0:40:38.35,0:40:41.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,挑战已知的物理学法则.\N{\rasEng}that defy the laws of known physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.98,0:40:46.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这意味着宇宙中所有的物质粒子\N{\rasEng}It would mean all matter particles in the universe
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.05,0:40:48.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,都像是这棵树上的树叶.\N{\rasEng}are like the leaves on this tree.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:48.89,0:40:53.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,而一个无形的非粒子树干则是它们的根基,\N{\rasEng}An invisible tree of unparticles may be their anchor,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:53.90,0:40:58.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,隐秘地支撑起整个宇宙.\N{\rasEng}the secret underpinning of the entire cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.30,0:41:01.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Georgi: 这正是非粒子物理的观点.\N{\rasEng}Georgi: That's really the point of unparticle physics.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:01.34,0:41:05.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,为了让这棵无形的树变得有趣,\N{\rasEng}In order for this invisible tree to be interesting,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:05.84,0:41:07.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就需要让它在某种程度上\N{\rasEng}it has to somehow interact
Dialogue: 0,0:41:07.44,0:41:10.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,与标准模型中的粒子相互作用.\N{\rasEng}with the particles of the standard model.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:10.01,0:41:13.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,树叶需要以某种方式长在树干上,\N{\rasEng}The leaves will have to somehow be held up by that tree
Dialogue: 0,0:41:13.31,0:41:15.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,树干上也需要有树叶.\N{\rasEng}or vice versa.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.35,0:41:17.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：至今,\N{\rasEng}Freeman: So far,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.79,0:41:21.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,LHC的实验尚未表明非粒子的迹象,\N{\rasEng}there are no signs of unparticles at the LHC.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.96,0:41:27.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,但Howard作为一个非粒子物理学家是不会放弃的.\N{\rasEng}But Howard isn't giving up as an unparticle physicist.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:27.13,0:41:30.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,坦白地说我不认为我们得到的是正确的图景.\N{\rasEng}I don't think we've got the right picture frankly.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.40,0:41:32.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,当你有些奇怪的东西,\N{\rasEng}When you have something that strange
Dialogue: 0,0:41:32.83,0:41:37.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,与我们所知的都不一样,\N{\rasEng}and that different from what we know,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.44,0:41:39.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这就显得非常诱人.\N{\rasEng}it's tantalizing.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:39.47,0:41:42.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,这样,我认为这是值得继续下去\N{\rasEng}And so,I think it's worth continuing
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.24,0:41:45.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,尝试解决掉这个复杂的数学计算,\N{\rasEng}to try to beat on this complicated mathematics
Dialogue: 0,0:41:45.55,0:41:47.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,并看看能否取得更多进步.\N{\rasEng}and see if can make some more progress.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.72,0:41:52.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,弗里曼：希格斯玻色子真的是上帝粒子吗？\N{\rasEng}Freeman: Is the Higgs boson really the God particle？
Dialogue: 0,0:41:52.15,0:41:54.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,还是某些更深层次、\N{\rasEng}Or is there something else underneath,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.86,0:41:57.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,更加神秘的东西？\N{\rasEng}something more mysterious？
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.19,0:41:59.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们存在的理由\N{\rasEng}Do we owe our existence
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.93,0:42:03.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,应该归于我们从未检测到的东西吗？\N{\rasEng}to something we might never detect？
Dialogue: 0,0:42:03.10,0:42:05.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,就现在来说,科学家继续研究\N{\rasEng}For now,scientists continue to probe
Dialogue: 0,0:42:05.23,0:42:08.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们成功发现的上帝粒子,\N{\rasEng}the God particle they have triumphantly discovered,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:08.77,0:42:13.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希望有一天他们能发现答案.\N{\rasEng}hoping they will one day find out.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:13.04,0:42:17.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,希格斯玻色子和我们玩了几十年的\N{\rasEng}The Higgs boson has been playing a game of hide-and-seek
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.25,0:42:18.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,捉迷藏,\N{\rasEng}for decades.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.35,0:42:21.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,现在我们终于发现了它,\N{\rasEng}Now that we have finally found it,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:21.15,0:42:23.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,或是类似于它的东西,\N{\rasEng}or something like it,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.35,0:42:27.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,我们的问题比答案更多.\N{\rasEng}we have more questions than answers.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.09,0:42:30.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,物理学家每次找到一扇门的钥匙,\N{\rasEng}Each time physicists find the key to one door,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:30.93,0:42:34.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,他们打开门却发现还有另一扇紧锁的门,\N{\rasEng}they open it just to find,another door.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:34.61,0:42:36.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,然后现在,又有五扇门.\N{\rasEng}And then,five more.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:37.21,0:42:40.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,也许希格斯玻色子的确是上帝粒子.\N{\rasEng}Maybe the Higgs boson really is,God's particle.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:41.49,0:42:45.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,一个宇宙谜题的解答,却正是另一个谜题.\N{\rasEng}A cosmic puzzle whose solution,is just another puzzle.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:46.43,0:42:49.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,宇宙留给我们的,注定都是谜题.\N{\rasEng}Destined to remain,an enigma.
